            <h2>City of Alaminos</h2>
            <h3>Home of the Hundred Islands</h3>

            <img src="<?= $this->webroot ?>theme/weatherph/img/tourism/alaminos1.png" alt="">
            <p>
                Alaminos City is the heart of Western Pangasinan. It is rich in natural and man-made attractions like the world famous Hun- dred Islands National Park, making tourism a flourishing indus- try. The Hundred Islands boasts of pristine beauty, white sand beaches and cool, clear waters. Other spots in the City are the Baleyadaan Ruins — the seat of Alaminos during the Spanish era, now the site of church ruins - and the Pag-Asinan, featuring the salt-making industry which Pangasinan is known for.
            </p>
            <p>
                The City of Alaminos lies along the shore of the historical Lingayen Gulf. It is bounded on the north by the Lingayen Gulf where the Hundred Islands can be found; on the east by the Municipality of Sual; on the south by the Municipality of Mabini; and on the west by the Municipality of Bani.
            </p>
            <p>
                Some highly sought foods in the City include the boneless ban- gus (milkfish), goat meat, parad (spareribs) and longganisa (sau- sage).
            </p>
            <p>
                Alaminians pay homage to its patron saint, St. Joseph, every third week of March through a colorful celebration called Gali-La Hundred Islands Festival.
            </p>

            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    1. The City fiesta in honor of Patron Saint Joseph and the Gali-La Hundred Islands Festival (third week of March, actual fiesta is March 19) – This festival is the most anticipated event in Alaminos City showcasing a range of activities from different arts and performance competitions, various fun-filled activities such as concerts of famous artists and a city-wide street party and agri-trade fair.
                </li>
                <li>
                    2. Village fiestas – All the 39 barangays (villages) of Alaminos City celebrate their own fiesta to honor their individual patron saints. Each home in the barangay serves sumptuous food to friends and guests. Barangay fiesta starts as early as first week of December (in Brgy. Pangapisan) and runs up to May (in Brgy. Maawi). Moro-Moro or Zarzuela, the traditional musical play, is often presented during barangay fiestas.
                </li>
                <li>
                    3. The Gali-Langoy Eco-Adventure Race – This is celebrated every Labor Day (May 1) where the City hosts swimming, parao racing, kayaking and other water sports competition. The most unique feature is the island-to-island race. It is a growing popu- lar attraction in the City.
                </li>
                <li>4. The Ban-oitan Ed Alaminos – This sport fishing competition is held every September 29. It is one of the highlights of the celebration of the turnover of the Hundred Island National Park from the Philippine Tourism Authority to Alaminos City. The competition promotes the hook and line fishing which is legal, safe and environment-friendly. Competitors vie for the biggest fish catch and heaviest fish, among others.</li>
                <li>5. The Underwater Weddings – Experience Valentine’s Day (February 14) with an extraordinary underwater wedding or watch hundreds of couples exchange “I Do's” every February 14 in either one of these romantic locations — Bolo Beach, Lucap Wharf, or the Hundred Islands.</li>
            </ol>

