            <h3>City of Alaminos’ Must Do List</h3>

            <ol>
                <li>
                    1. Go on a Hundred Islands adventure. Explore and see what works for you from a host of island activities. Check out the giant clams or go snorkeling, cliff diving, island hopping, spelunking, fun-fishing, parasailing, jet skiing, kayaking, scuba diving, banana boat riding, birdwatching, or simply sun bathing anywhere in the 123 islands of your choice. If you are lucky enough, you might just get a rare peek of visiting whales and dolphins.
                </li>
                <li>
                    2. Savor the Alaminos longganisa. One distinct feature of this variant of Philippine sausage (chorizo) is that its ends are sealed with little sticks. But what stands out is its garlicky and slightly salty taste. It is best when charbroiled and dipped in a spicy condiment.
                </li>
                <li>
                    3. Check out Camantiles Island Eco-Trail Park and explore its flora and fauna. It is the only island that can be reached by hiking. An island, is it? Years and years of wave movement created a sandbar that connected it to the mainland. Trails leading into the island’s deep forest recesses have been created—a nature lover’s dream. Or as an alternative, try the Bued Mangrove Park.
                </li>
                <li>
                    4. Buy a shellcraft at the Lucap Wharf. These expertly crafted mementos speak of the artistry and patience of the Ala- minos shellcraft makers. Some are great adornments to grace a living room or add a touch of the sea in a veranda or a cabana.
                </li>
                <li>
                    5. Discover Alaminos City’s best practices. Visit the Maria Valdez Cornelia Techno-Demo Farm located in the village of Tangcarang and check out its hybrid and organic agricultural products. One may also drop by Tangcarang Elementary School, one of the 45 schools in the city that is connected through the city’s innovative WINGS project (also known as Wireless Internet-based Governance System). Immerse in any of the schools and learn about the city’s Bright Child, an integrated program that targets education, social welfare and development, health and nutrition, and sports and cultural awareness.
                </li>
            </ol>

